        </div>
        <div class="text">
          <div class="item">
            <h1>That Old Spreadsheet with brazilian VC funds...</h1>
            <p>
              The year was 2008. I was just one more nerd, curious about 
              all the chosen paths of the called Web 2.0.
            </p>
            <p>
              On that time, I was reading and consuming a large amount of
              content and tendencies of the brazilian digital market.
              Preparing to launch the brazilian version of ReadWrite (RIP).
            </p>
            <p>
              As I was looking to learn and understand the venture capital
              market, merges and acquisitions, I felt the need of catalog and
              organize informations about the brazilian market, for future queries
              and as personal annotations. So, everything started.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="item">
            <h1>The birth of the spreadsheet</h1>
            <p>
              On that time informations wasn't very widespread and few people
              were on this market. So I started a spreadsheet, lovely called
              the “Brazil Startup Dealbook”, inspired by the Dealbook section,
              from New York Times.
            </p>
            <p>
              On the first version, the Dealbook was just for personal reference.
              I was following the news about startups and was trying to catalog
              through there, but the only one with access to the data was me.
            </p>
            <p>The spreadsheet has only 6 columns:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Deal date;</li>
              <li>Company name;</li>
              <li>Deal type: Investment, merge or acquisition?;</li>
              <li>Amount;</li>
              <li>Fund name/buyer;</li>
              <li>Link to the information source.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>It has a new tab for each year, starting in 2007.</p>
            <p>It was simple, but worked well.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="box-img-table">
          <img src="/img/img-table.jpg" class="img-responsive" alt="">
          <span>Picture of the birth of Monashees Capital, in 2007</span>
        </div>
        <div class="text">
          <div class="item">
            <p>
              However, on the following year happened something that made things
              much more serious on the investment and startups market in Brazil.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="item">
            <h1>Enter Buscapé:</h1>
            <p>
              In september 2009 the Naspers group (a midea conglomerate from 
              South Africa) annouced the acquisition of Buscapé, by US$342 mi. 
              
              Soon, startups and venture capital investments became something
              cool in Brazil.
            </p>
            <p>
              The market, almost dead previously, started to move. Investors
              as Monashees, Tiger Global, Naspers and others started to
              accelerate the investments on the country. Rapidly Brazil started
              to have news about investments, merges and acquisitions more
              frequently.
            </p>
            <p>
              In a small timestamp I wasn't more able to follow every deals
              on the country. Then, in 2011, I started to think about
              potentials benefits of the Crowdsourcing to Dealbook.
              Uploaded the spreadsheet on Google Drive and started
              slowly, sharing “my precious” with a few near entrepreneurs.
            </p>
            <p>
              The Google Drive format was nice, as it allowed other 
              people to include new deals and, in small steps, the database
              started to grow. To include a new business, the only
              things needed were a link to an article and the deal date.
            </p>
            <p>
              As I was living with many entrepreneurs and was always talking
              about the market, many times a week I got myself sending the
              spreadsheet URL to some investor or someone looking for an
              investment. On the 10th time that I shared my creation, realized
              that could turn it into a public source, open and free to the
              entire community.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="item">
            <h1>Going Public</h1>
            <p>
              In 2011 published the spreadsheet to the world (see the post on
              Startupi) and it really started to grow fast. On the publish
              date, for example, the spreadsheet has only 85 deals. But 42 of
              them were made until that day, untill November.
            </p>
            <p>A primeira grande ajuda veio de um parceiro de curadoria/moderação. O Luciano Tavares, fundador da Magnetis, estava fazendo alguns investimentos anjo (Disclosure: Ele é investidor-anjo na Rock Content) e curtiu bastante a ideia da planilha, começando então a contribuir com frequência.</p>
            <p>Rapidamente estávamos nos tornando a base de dados oficial de VC no Brasil e até atualizamos ainda mais a planilha incluindo investimentos de anos anteriores, tentando traçar com mais detalhes a história do Venture Capital no país. Sim, escavamos todos os deals de venture capital públicos BR que conseguimos encontrar. Legal, não?</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="box-img">
          <img src="/img/img-grafico-dealbook.jpg" class="img-responsive" alt="">
          <span>Gráfico: Novos Deals catalogados no Dealbook, por ano</span>
        </div>
        <div class="text">
          <div class="item">
            <h1>E o Caos Reina…</h1>
            <p>Com o crescimento no volume de deals, e mais pessoas com acesso à planilha, rapidamente ela ganhou vida própria. A cada dia, mais colaboradores adicionavam novas transações. Alguns chegavam a criar novas abas como listas de VCs, anjos, aceleradoras e muito mais.</p>
            <p>Tivemos algumas vandalizações pontuais, mas o Google Drive tornava fácil reverter e banir os culpados. Aos poucos, a comunidade aprendeu a se policiar e só tivemos que reverter os dados para versões anteriores algumas poucas vezes.</p>
            <p>Em pouco tempo estávamos batendo o limite máximo de colaboradores do Google Drive e o Lu veio com uma ideia. Ele me mandou uma mensagem no chat mais ou menos assim:</p>
            <div class="depo">
